Title#1: Burma, Penang, and China in the 1920s : four photograph albums
Alternative Title#1: Four photograph albums by George West Philleo
Abstract#1: Consists of approximately 150 vintage photographs housed in 4 photograph albums comprising images of Burma, Penang and China, with a small black leather bound "line a day" journal of George West Philleo from 1917 to 1924. There is also a photograph showing a Chinese rickshaw driver asleep on his wooden cart in Shanghai, China. Most of the photographs are of the region around Mandalay and capture a time now long gone.

Abstract#1: A photograph showing the front of a children's school in Mawlamyine (previously Moulmein), Myanmar (Burma). It is a white school building with two stories, with the windows having wooden shutters as well as rounded entryways. On the second story, curtains can be seen over the entry ways. On the upper balcony as well as in the ground level entry way, 12 people are standing and looking towards the camera. The building is surrounded by trees and grass. The title is written on back of the photograph.
Note#1: Collection origin: Ira Wolff Photographic History Collection
Note#2: This photograph is part of a set of 19 photographs of British colonial Burma (Myanmar), very likely taken by British colonists who lived in the area in the late 19th century. Title#1: Photograph album of colonial French Indochina 1890-1900
Abstract#1: One photograph album containing 76 original albumen and gelatin silver photographs of French Indochina in the 1890s. Images were taken by a French colonial resident of the area, most include handwritten captions in French. Photographs show a variety of people and places including Saigon, Tan An, Tra Vinh, Can Tho, Bac Lieu, Soc Trang, the mansion and tomb of Tran Ba Loc in Ca Bei, a Lao village, scenes of a river regatta and public festivities, the ruins of Angkor Wat, portraits of Lao warriors, Vietnamese indigenous people from the Central Highlands, furniture factory workers, and French colonial residents and their families.
Physical Location#1: University of Colorado Boulder Libraries Rare and Distinctive Collections

Title#1: Photographs of colonial Indonesia, New Guinea and Pacific Islands 1900-1905
Abstract#1: Consists of 34 thick card stock leaves with 151 original photographs, including 85 views of Java, Ambon, Sulawesi and Banda Islands, 28 views of New Guinea, 35 views of Samoa, Tonga and Fiji. The album includes three large albumen photographs of the official procession during the 1903 Delhi Durbar which commemorated the coronation of King Edward VII and Queen Alexandra as Emperor and Empress of India. Most photographs have manuscript captions in ink on the mounts related to either the individual image or to groups of images.

Alternative Title#1: Bookseller's title: Two albums of original photographs taken by an American traveler in Japan
Abstract#1: Consists of two black morocco bound albums with gilt lettered titles on the spines and marbled endpapers; contain over 310 mounted gelatin silver photographs (ranging from 11 x 15 cm to 4 x 5 cm) with white ink captions in English. [Vol. 1] depicts mountain scenery in Banff, Canada, followed by scenes of Japanese street life and landscapes, ending with images of the Pacific Ocean and boats near San Francisco -- [vol. 2] depicts images of the steamer, Empress of India, in Vancouver, B.C., followed by scenes of Japan, ending with an image of Waikiki Beach, Honolulu.

Abstract#1: A photograph of a residence in Yangon (previously Rangoon), Myanmar (Burma). The image shows a large home with two Burmese workers dressed in all white clothing, while British individuals are taking their tea in front of the house, adorned in traditional western style clothes including one man in a top hat and the other two in pith helmets. Also seen in the photograph is a horse drawn carriage that fits under the porch of the residence. The title is written on the back of the photograph. It is possible that these individuals were also the ones who photographed the other images of Myanmar in this collection of 19 loose images.
Note#1: Collection origin: Ira Wolff Photographic History Collection
Note#2: This photograph is part of a set of 19 photographs of British colonial Burma (Myanmar), very likely taken by British colonists who lived in the area in the late 19th century. One of the photographs in the set is of a group of British people outside a large mansion, who may have been those taking the photographs.
